{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500778"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:17:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:17:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1670"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1670"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.05,0.77,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41876"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1670"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"450"},{"type":"tags","id":"2083"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44774"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41876"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with early satiety and a resultant loss of 10 kilograms over the past three months. He has also been lethargic and nauseated after meals. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears cachectic and pale. Abdominal examination reveals a painful swelling in his umbilicus (Image 1, 2). There is also a swelling in the left supraclavicular fossa. There are no other significant findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paraumbilical hernia","Pyogenic granuloma","Pyoderma gangrenosum","Metastatic deposit","Omphalitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of a Sister Mary Joseph\u0027s nodule and is a \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic deposit\u003C/strong\u003E, usually gastrointestinal in origin. This sign is frequently associated with internal malignancy in the gastrointestinal tract (52%) and female genital tract (28%). In this case, the patient is likely to have gastric carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParaumbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as the defect would be adjacent to the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the umbilicus and occurs commonly in neonates. It is an unlikely diagnosis in this case due to the age of the patient as well as the absence of surrounding erythema and purulent discharge from the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyogenic granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E is often confused with malignancy as it presents as a painless, vascular node with rapid growth. They are however most commonly seen to be located in the head and neck region, nails and limbs. In addition, they appear to be smooth or lobulated with reddish/bluish hue. These features are not visible in the case above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyoderma gangrenosum\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition that presents as a rapidly enlarging painful ulcer in patients with inflammatory bowel disease. The above image does not appear to be ulcerated, making this an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sister Mary Joseph\u0027s nodules are metastatic deposits at the umbilicus/paraumbilical region, frequently associated with internal malignancy in the gastrointestinal tract (52%) and female genital tract (28%)"],"references":["Painter K, Anand S, Philip K. Omphalitis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513338/","Wollina U, Langner D, Fran\u00e7a K, Gianfaldoni S, Lotti T, Tchernev G. Pyogenic Granuloma - A Common Benign Vascular Tumor with Variable Clinical Presentation: New Findings and Treatment Options. Open Access Maced J Med Sci. 2017;5(4):423-426. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5535648/","Oakley A. Pyoderma gangrenosum. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2015. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/pyoderma-gangrenosum/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26848"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1670"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"10279"},{"type":"media","id":"10280"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"10279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/10279"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1c0b0bc3-54ef-4e12-b28d-1f88f1936e5a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1c0b0bc3-54ef-4e12-b28d-1f88f1936e5a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":406}},{"type":"media","id":"10280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/10280"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6f794b2e-85e5-4723-9825-e371a6538abf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6f794b2e-85e5-4723-9825-e371a6538abf.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":497,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26848"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-25T21:04:09+10:30","updatedAt":